{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537256"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15980"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608043"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15980"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15980"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.05,0.04,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8671"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86420"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8671"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70699"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"2163"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"},{"type":"tags","id":"7215"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8201"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44969"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86420"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman is reviewed on the ward following a right hemithyroidectomy for a 3 cm thyroid nodule. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The surgical site appears clean and dry. When speaking, her voice is notably hoarse compared to preoperatively. She reports no pain or difficulty breathing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for her voice change?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury","Laryngeal oedema","Endotracheal tube trauma","External laryngeal nerve injury","Vocal cord haematoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with post-thyroidectomy hoarseness, which is most commonly caused by injury to the recurrent laryngeal nerve. The recurrent laryngeal nerve runs in close proximity to the thyroid gland and is at risk during thyroid surgery, particularly when dissecting the inferior pole of the thyroid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecurrent laryngeal nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E causes ipsilateral vocal cord paralysis, resulting in immediate post-operative hoarseness. While concerning, most cases are temporary due to nerve stretching or inflammation rather than complete transection, with recovery typically occurring within 6-12 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal laryngeal nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes weakness of the cricothyroid muscle, affecting voice pitch rather than causing frank hoarseness. Patients usually notice difficulty with high-pitched sounds or voice fatigue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaryngeal oedema\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes stridor and breathing difficulties in addition to voice changes. It would be unusual to have isolated hoarseness without other symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal tube trauma\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a sore throat and mild voice changes that resolve within 24-48 hours. It would be unusual for this to cause significant hoarseness in isolation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVocal cord haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare complication that would typically be associated with pain and potentially breathing difficulties. It would be unusual without direct trauma to the vocal cords.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe appropriate next step would be to perform laryngoscopy to confirm the diagnosis and document the position and movement of the vocal cords. This helps with prognosis and guides management, which may include speech therapy and close follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury is the most common cause of post-thyroidectomy hoarseness, occurring in 1-2% of cases.","Hoarseness immediately after thyroid surgery should be investigated with laryngoscopy to assess vocal cord function.","Most cases of post-thyroidectomy recurrent laryngeal nerve injury are temporary and resolve within 6-12 months."],"references":["Jiang Y, Gao B, Zhang X, Zhao J, Chen J, Zhang S, Luo D. Prevention and treatment of recurrent laryngeal nerve injury in thyroid surgery. Int J Clin Exp Med. 2014 Jan 15;7(1):101-7. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3902246/","Joliat GR, Guarnero V, Demartines N, et al. Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury after thyroid and parathyroid surgery: Incidence and postoperative evolution assessment. Medicine 2017;96(17):e6674. Available at: https://journals.lww.com/md-journal/fulltext/2017/04280/recurrent_laryngeal_nerve_injury_after_thyroid_and.15.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70699"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15980"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70699"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-21T09:47:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-21T09:47:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8671"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86420"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"c